The codebase is actually lean (~950 source lines; the 6k diff figure is dominated by package-lock.json at 4,981 lines, and `out/sample.mp4` is untracked/gitignored). No useMemo abuse, no style-constant bloat, no dead exports found. The real simplification value is in a handful of copy-paste patterns that matter precisely because this is the reference pack contributors will duplicate.

```json
[
  {
    "file": "remotion/src/scenes/Caption.tsx",
    "line": 4,
    "summary": "Caption takes a precomputed `opacity` prop, so all four scenes (Title, Action, Showcase, Stats) each hand-roll a near-identical clamped `captionIn` interpolate block and Classic.tsx additionally passes `caption={scene.caption}` even though `scene` (which contains `caption`) is already a prop. Simpler form: Caption accepts `enterAt` (frame) and calls useCurrentFrame to own its own fade (it can also render null on empty text, killing the four `{caption ? ... : null}` guards); scenes render `<Caption text={scene.caption} enterAt={8} />` and drop both the separate `caption` prop and their interpolate blocks.",
    "failure_scenario": "This is the reference pack: every genre pack copies 4 scene files, so the fade math and prop plumbing get duplicated 4x per pack. Tweaking caption fade duration or easing later means editing every scene in every pack instead of one component."
  },
  {
    "file": "remotion/src/scenes/Showcase.tsx",
    "line": 57,
    "summary": "Three parallel conditionals branch on scene.verdict: chained ternaries for `verdictColor` (l.57-58) and `verdictLabel` (l.59-60), plus a third partial ternary for the banner background (l.179) that already drifted — 'reveal' gets greenBg behind a purple border/text. Simpler form: one `VERDICT: Record<verdict, {color, bg, label}>` lookup used in all three places.",
    "failure_scenario": "The drift has already happened once (reveal banner is green-on-purple). Anyone adjusting verdict styling must find and sync three separate expressions; pack copiers inherit the inconsistency."
  },
  {
    "file": "remotion/src/scenes/Showcase.tsx",
    "line": 32,
    "summary": "The animation schedule is spread across three parallel structures rebuilt from scratch on every frame render: `removedIndexes`, `addedIndexes`, and a `typeStarts` Map keyed by line index, with `removedIndexes.indexOf(i)` re-searched inside the render loop for each removed line. Simpler form: one pre-pass building a single `schedule` array aligned with `lines` (per-line `{start, dur}` or collapse order), so the render loop just reads `schedule[i]` and the Map/indexOf/filter machinery disappears.",
    "failure_scenario": "This is the most complex scene component (239 lines) in the template. Contributors adding a phase (e.g. TestRun/Screenshot artifacts per the TODO in types.ts) must reverse-engineer how three index structures interlock; the indexOf-inside-map pattern invites off-by-one staggering bugs when copied."
  },
  {
    "file": "remotion/src/scenes/Title.tsx",
    "line": 37,
    "summary": "`captionIn` wraps a clamped interpolate in a redundant `doneTyping ? ... : 0` guard (the clamp already returns 0 before the range starts) and inlines `typingStart + scene.task.length / charsPerFrame` twice in one 150+ char line. Simpler form: `const typingEnd = typingStart + scene.task.length / charsPerFrame;` then a plain `interpolate(frame, [typingEnd + 5, typingEnd + 20], [0, 1], clamp)` — no conditional.",
    "failure_scenario": "The duplicated expression is the scene's timing linchpin; editing one copy but not the other (e.g. changing charsPerFrame handling) silently desyncs the caption fade. The dead conditional also teaches template copiers a wrong pattern (guarding clamped interpolates)."
  },
  {
    "file": "remotion/src/scenes/Stats.tsx",
    "line": 20,
    "summary": "The `{ extrapolateLeft: 'clamp', extrapolateRight: 'clamp' }` options object is repeated verbatim in 13 interpolate calls across the four scenes, most following the same `[start, start+dur] -> [0, 1]` shape; Stats already extracted local `pop`/`countUp` helpers proving the pattern. Simpler form: hoist a tiny shared helper (e.g. `fade(frame, start, dur, easing?)` plus `pop`) into a shared anim util next to theme.ts, or at minimum a shared `CLAMP` const to spread.",
